<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>    L</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->ately I've been searching the WWW for information on my favorite fighter of all time. During this process I've taken in a lot of info on both Tekken and Virtua Fighter. I've come here to lay it all down in one LONG post. I'm here to discuss with others these two beloved fighters. Which do you prefer? I'm looking for more of a preference here. It's been discussed, sure, but here it is right out in the open. Both games are great and sure its kinda like comparing apples and oranges, but here we go....<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>       My Choice</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->: Virtua Fighter<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>       Why?</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->: Its a fighter I've played for many years. My first 3d fighter. Virtua Fighter 2 on Sega Saturn was the beginning. For the time, the graphics were above and beyond what any other system had. The animation was fluid and the moves were incredibly inumerable. To put it lightly I was awed by this game. I cant quite put my finger on it, but something about this game gripped me and didnt let me go. After this every other fighter was just second best. Nothing ever felt right to me. Now years later I've been able to more or less figure out why.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>       Gameplay/Graphics</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->: Being only about 10-11 when I first played, I found it nice to be able to come in and get through a few levels with my limited moves and eventually get stopped dead in my tracks later on. Virtua Fighter lends some ease in letting people scratch the surface of a game with limited knowledge and slowly pull you into something much more deep. Over the next year and a half I learned more and more moves. Looking back it's overwhelming how much there was to keep being discovered. If you keep at the game and most importantly retain what you &quot;learned&quot; the game sorta becomes part of your mind. For lack of a better analogy it's like learning a martial art. You gotta practice and remember how to do the moves (I would know I was two steps away from a black belt a few years ago and I dropped it). Each character has there style and I find it hard to really learn more than one character fully. You gotta choose who you like. OR if you prefer you can learn many characters but not as much.<br>
<br>
Now the graphics. Each Virtua Fighter has brought something very impressive to the table graphics-wise. The most groundbreaking would be Virtua Fighter. The first true 3d fighter. So revolutionary that its on display at the Smithsonian. Nothing like it had ever been around. Groundbreaking. For some the whole Virtua Fighter style isnt for them. For me it was something (at the time) that was completely foreign to me. Everything in the game was new. I had never seen such &quot;oriental&quot; influenced levels and costumes.(oriental is not meant to be offensive, just describing the culture portrayed by the game, how it felt to me) Virtua Fighter 2 was even better. The Saturn port was less dazzling, but it was better than any other fighter out at the time. Virtua Fighter 3 blew away the competition when it came out in theatres. It was lightyears ahead of the graphics in Tekken Tag Tournament (aracade version). Unfortunately by the time it hit the Dreamcast it had lost its impact. To tell the truth though I enjoy Virtua Fighter 3 very much. It retained eveything I like about the first two, but gave it a new cover. I wasnt looking for earth shattering, and frankly this was enough for me. The game was still there and under all the changes, it was the Virtua Fighter I loved. Sure the voices were changed from their classic-ness and were much worse, it was what I liked. Virtua Fighter 4, I'm embarassed to say, I havent had the opportunity to play yet. I've bought it, but I'm still waiting about two more paychecks before I can afford the actual system. I can say this though. If the game is able to retain it's style, music, gameplay,and graphics (which it seems it has) I will be MORE than satisfied. Am I biased? A little. I've been more or less raised on this fighter, but I saw Tekken the whole time. Not as much but I did. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>       What About Tekken?</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->: I really enjoy Tekken, I really do. Especially recently I've tried to warm up to it. And I have. The games pacing and style are very good. I enjoy the characters and controls, but I dont feel at home. I've looked up some moves and tried to get into the deepness of this game. The deeper, harder moves and a whole new dimension to the play. The problem is, it seems like this game is too easy to win. I fought my cousin who is as die hard for Tekken as I am for Virtua Fighter and I very nearly won a few times. This is my only true gripe with the game. The other reasons are purely personal preference. I will admit Tekken has a much more &quot;there&quot; story. When you win, you see the characters story. In Virtua Fighter you pretty much just win. The story is in the character bios in the instruction manual. You find out what each character did after the tournament in the sequels instruction book. Tekken is much better at conveying its story. Virtua Fighter seems a little more original and willing to try new things. Tekken has more or less used the same formula from square one. Graphics got better, but the fighting stayed more or less the same (which is a good thing). Virtua Fighter seemed to add something with each new installment. In some cases it worked (the option for ring outs, cant remember if the were in the original VF, but this definately worked) and in some cases it failed (side step button in VF3). At least they went for something new. Back to Tekken, if I am incorrect about new additions I apologise because I dont know the Tekken games as well I do the VF games.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>       Conclusion</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->: Virtua Fighter is my choice. Tekken seems like a fun little romp for good measure (to me). I could never get down with Tekken and feel part of it. I look forward to the responses from you guys, because this is one of the best boards for Tekken/VF discussion. I only ask a few things for responding to this please (I'm in the mood for an awesome debate):<br>
1) Lets try to keep it civilized as usual. No name calling or even personal attacks and the like.<br>
2) Support what you say with details.<br>
3) Dont come in with &quot;Marvel vs. Capcom is the best hands down.&quot; Or DOA, Soul Calibur, or any other fighter. I like those too, but its for another topic.<br>
4) Like I mentioned I'm in the mood for a serious discussion with other seasoned Tekken/VF players. I look forward to this and just hope people are willing to run with this.<br>
<br>
