<br>
First off, let me clear my cousins name cause he'd kill me if he read this (which he wont). I exagerrated. I got close maybe once or twice. He wasnt even using his characters (Hwoarang and Bayak ((or something to that effect))). While using those two he's almost unstoppable.<br>
<br>
Now back to the topic. What was it about Tekken 3 in particular that made it better than VF3? Or Virtua Fighter for that matter. Tekken 3 seems intersting enough, but when I compare it to the likes of VF2 (but not so much VF3) it doesnt seem to measure up. Where I see the better-ness is in the extras. Namco is always good for adding in extra goods. As to your comment on using combo strings against certain opponents to win and in Tekken you need to be more &quot;strategic&quot; (or something to that effect), I think that VF has just as much strategy to it. Especially in this newest incarnation where combos and reversals all play a part. But in retrospect it may seem hard for both of us to really &quot;know&quot; the game if we dont love it and dig in to it as we do our respective fighter. Where I see Tekken as sorta &quot;stiff&quot;, you see VF as sorta &quot;basic&quot; (I think, from your post). <br>
